4 SYNOPSIS:
5 The Alabama Resilience Council was established
6 by Executive Order No. 736 to provide a forum for
7 coordinating activities of state government and for
8 facilitating interactions between state and local
9 government and the private sector to proactively
10 address harmful impacts on Alabama communities and
11 infrastructure before they occur.
12 This bill would permanently establish the
13 Alabama Resilience Council as an appointed advisory
14 group within the executive branch of state government.
15 This bill would provide for the rules, duties,
16 and procedures of the council.
17 This bill would authorize appointment of, and
18 provide for the responsibilities of, a Chief Resilience
19 Officer.
20 This bill would also require a statewide
21 resilience plan that includes a statewide comprehensive
22 risk and vulnerability assessment.
23
24
25 A BILL
26 TO BE ENTITLED
27 AN ACT
28
Page 1

29 To create the Alabama Resilience Council as an
30 appointed advisory group within the executive branch of state
31 government, and to provide for the rules, duties, and
32 procedures of the council; to authorize appointment of, and
33 provide for the responsibilities of, a Chief Resilience
34 Officer; to require a statewide resilience plan that includes
35 a statewide comprehensive risk and vulnerability assessment;
36 and to create the Office of Risk and Resilience within the
37 Department of Insurance.
38 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
39 Section 1. The Legislature finds and declares the
40 following:
41 (1) Alabama is susceptible to various natural and
42 manmade disaster events, posing threats to the safety of its
43 citizens, integrity of its infrastructure, prospects for its
44 economic growth, and maintenance and protection of its unique
45 natural resources. These threats also pose significant fiscal
46 and operational risks to functions of the state and local
47 government.
48 (2) For the purposes of this act, the term "resilience"
49 shall be considered the capacity of individuals, communities,
50 businesses, and systems to anticipate, prepare for, adapt to,
51 and rapidly recover from adverse events. For the purposes of
52 this act, resilience shall be guided by five principles: (i)
53 individual responsibility; (ii) collective continuity and
54 function; (iii) factual assessment of risk; (iv) integrated
55 resilience efforts; and (v) focused support.
56 (3) The Alabama Resilience Council established by
Page 2

(3) The Alabama Resilience Council established by
57 Executive Order No. 736, on May 5, 2023, has examined
58 resilience policy needs to address current and future adverse
59 events, and based on its findings, Alabama would benefit from
60 a lasting, comprehensive approach to resilience.
61 (4) Coordinated statewide resilience efforts and
62 development of a statewide resilience plan would be most
63 effective under a single designated Chief Resilience Officer
64 to coordinate activities of the Alabama Resilience Council.
65 Section 2. (a) Commencing upon the Governor's
66 rescission of Executive Order No. 736, the Alabama Resilience
67 Council shall be created as an appointed advisory group within
68 the executive branch of state government for the purpose of
69 coordinating resilience-related activities of state government
70 and for facilitating interactions between state and local
71 government and the private sector to proactively address
72 harmful impacts on Alabama communities and infrastructure
73 before they occur.
74 (b) The voting members of the council shall consist of
75 the Governor or his or her designee, the Chief Resilience
76 Officer, and the head of the following agencies or their
77 designees:
78 (1) The Department of Agriculture and Industries.
79 (2) The Department of Commerce.
80 (3) The Department of Conservation and Natural
81 Resources.
82 (4) The Alabama Department of Economic and Community
83 Affairs.
84 (5) The Alabama Department of Environmental Management.
