123 (d) The council membership shall be inclusive and
124 reflect the racial, gender, geographic, urban, rural, and
125 economic diversity of the state.
126 Section 3. The duties of the Alabama Resilience Council
127 shall be as follows:
128 (1) Develop strategies to guide statewide resilience
129 efforts by prioritizing objectives reflecting pressing
130 resilience challenges. To this end, the council shall
131 regularly convene government and private-sector stakeholders
132 with different perspectives and interests to facilitate
133 planning across jurisdictions and sectors and thereby to avoid
134 cascading failures. The council shall develop principles to
135 guide the work of state government in carrying out its
136 resilience initiatives.
137 (2) Assist the Chief Resilience Officer in the
138 development, maintenance, and implementation of the statewide
139 resilience plan.
140 (3) Solicit participation of the private sector in
Page 5

(3) Solicit participation of the private sector in
141 programs to collectively strengthen the resilience of
142 businesses and communities. The council shall engage the
143 private sector to reduce costs from lost productivity and
144 pursue joint, public-private efforts to avoid infrastructure
145 damages.
146 (4) Improve the public's ability to assess risk
147 management alternatives by reducing the complexity of risk
148 information for nontechnical audiences, by generating and
149 sharing reliable information that helps decision-makers
150 identify and select risk-reduction alternatives, and by
151 providing guidance about assistance programs and funding
152 opportunities based on needs, cost effectiveness, feasibility,
153 potential resources, and returns on investment.
154 (5) Develop, pursue, and support federal and state
155 policies and programs that promote innovative and flexible
156 solutions for achieving individual, community, and statewide
157 resilience.
158 (6) Provide support and assistance in the preparation
159 and maintenance of the state hazard mitigation plan, as
160 contemplated by the federal Disaster Mitigation Act of 2000,
161 42 U.S.C § 5121 et seq., or successor federal statute,
162 provided that the Alabama Emergency Management Agency shall be
163 responsible for administrative maintenance and day-to-day
164 execution of the plan.
165 (7) Identify and pursue funding opportunities to
166 promote resilience in the State of Alabama.
167 Section 4. (a) The council shall be led by a chair,
168 vice chair, cochairs, or other leadership positions from
Page 6

vice chair, cochairs, or other leadership positions from
169 within the voting membership on the council. Leadership
170 positions shall be appointed by the Governor and shall serve
171 at the pleasure of the Governor.
172 (b) The council shall develop, adopt, and maintain
173 bylaws governing its activities, provided the bylaws are
174 consistent with the provisions of this act. At its discretion,
175 the council may establish working groups or subcommittees.
176 (c) The council shall meet at least twice each year and
177 may meet more frequently upon the call of the chair, subject
178 to the Open Meetings Act. Members of the council may
179 participate in a meeting of the council by means of telephone
180 conference, video conference, or similar communications
181 equipment by means of which all individuals participating in
182 the meeting may hear each other at the same time.
183 Participation by electronic means shall constitute presence in
184 person at a meeting for all purposes.
185 (d) Members of the council shall serve without
186 compensation except members who are public officials or public
187 employees may elect to receive the per diem and travel
188 allowance authorized by state law for persons traveling on
189 official state business.
190 Section 5. (a) The Commissioner of Insurance shall
191 designate a Chief Resilience Officer within the Department of
192 Insurance to coordinate the activities of the council
193 established pursuant to Section 2 and lead the development,
194 maintenance, and implementation of the statewide resilience
195 plan.
196 (b) The duties of the Chief Resilience Officer shall be
Page 7

(b) The duties of the Chief Resilience Officer shall be
197 as follows:
198 (1) Conduct a comprehensive inventory of Alabama's
199 resilience assets.
200 (2) Identify areas of collaboration among state
201 agencies, areas of overlap, and potential shareable resources.
202 (3) Review resilience programs from both inside Alabama
203 and among comparable states.
204 (4) Engage state agencies to examine how to best
205 collect, organize, analyze, and communicate data in ways that
206 advance Alabama's resilience principles.
207 (5) Identify and enhance state agency knowledge of
208 statewide resilience efforts.
209 (6) Identify and pursue funding through federal, state,
210 and private opportunities to promote resilience in the State
211 of Alabama.
212 Section 6. (a) The Chief Resilience Officer shall
213 develop, maintain, and implement a statewide resilience plan,
214 with the general oversight and input from the council. The
215 plan shall include the following components:
216 (1) Statewide Comprehensive Risk and Vulnerability
217 Assessment. The plan shall evaluate the impacts of extreme
218 weather and disasters; assess current and future risks across
219 various hazards using historical data and future scenarios
220 while factoring in land and water management practices; and
221 examine effects on communities, infrastructure, the economy,
222 and the environment. Additionally, a vulnerability assessment
223 shall identify the social, economic, and environmental systems
224 most at risk. It shall analyze risk exposure, potential costs,
Page 8

most at risk. It shall analyze risk exposure, potential costs,
225 and impacts on state assets, government functions, local
226 economies, and critical natural systems.
227 (2) Resilience Actions. The plan shall provide a
228 prioritized list of resilience actions to address
229 vulnerabilities, detailing their benefits, costs, and
230 implementation timeline. Priority shall be given first to
231 actions that reduce state costs associated with historic and
232 persistent challenges or vulnerabilities that have calculable
233 costs or expenditures and that remediate or prevent critical
234 infrastructure failures that threaten public health, impair
235 essential services, or place the state at risk of federal
236 enforcement. Priority shall also be given to actions that
237 effectively mitigate the impacts of future disasters,
238 particularly those that provide multiple co-benefits, such as
239 enhancing environmental stewardship, economic stability, or
240 public health. Resilience actions that incorporate or restore
241 natural features to achieve risk mitigation benefits shall
242 also be prioritized, provided they are cost-effective and
243 demonstrate long-term advantages over alternative approaches.
244 The plan shall also outline how these actions align with
245 existing efforts by state agencies, local governments, and
246 other entities, ensuring they complement the state hazard
247 mitigation plan. Alabama state agencies engaged in resilience
248 activities shall report those activities to the Chief
249 Resilience Officer.
250 (3) Community Preparedness. The plan shall include
251 strategies to enhance community awareness to prepare for, and
252 protect against, hazards; to enable greater understanding of
Page 9

protect against, hazards; to enable greater understanding of
253 personal risks; to educate residents of the state about how to
254 mitigate risks; and to increase knowledge of resources
255 available for mitigation efforts.
256 (4) Implementation Strategy. The plan shall include an
257 implementation strategy outlining how resilience actions will
258 be enacted, funded, and tracked. It shall define roles,
259 responsibilities, timelines, and metrics while prioritizing
260 actions for high-risk vulnerabilities. The strategy shall also
261 support partnerships, provide technical assistance, and ensure
262 public access to data for planning and decision-making.
263 (b) The initial plan shall be completed within two
264 years after the effective date of this act and shall be
265 reviewed and updated at least every two years thereafter to
266 ensure its continued effectiveness and relevance.
267 Section 7. There is created a fund in the State
268 Treasury to be designated the "Alabama Resilience Council
269 Fund" to be used to support the activities of the Alabama
270 Resilience Council and the Chief Resilience Officer. The Chief
271 Resilience Officer may receive and deposit into or disburse
272 from the fund any federal, state, or private monies, in
273 accordance with applicable law. Receipts deposited into this
274 fund shall be disbursed only by warrants of the Comptroller
275 drawn upon the State Treasury on itemized vouchers approved by
276 the Commissioner of Insurance. No funds deposited pursuant to
277 Section 27-2-39, Code of Alabama 1975, shall be withdrawn or
278 expended except as budgeted and allotted according to Sections
279 41-4-80 to 41-4-96, inclusive, and 41-19-1 to 41-19-12,
280 inclusive, Code of Alabama 1975, and only in amounts as
Page 10

inclusive, Code of Alabama 1975, and only in amounts as
281 stipulated in the general fund appropriations act or other
282 appropriation acts. At the end of each fiscal year, any
283 unencumbered and unexpended balance shall not revert to the
284 State General Fund under Section 41-4-93, Code of Alabama
285 1975, but shall carry over to the next fiscal year.
286 Section 8. (a) There is created within the Department
287 of Insurance the Office of Risk and Resilience. The office
288 shall work to develop and implement programs that address risk
289 and resilience issues facing the state and, therefore, promote
290 a healthy insurance market. The senior director of the office
291 shall be appointed by the Commissioner of Insurance.
292 (b) The Commissioner of Insurance, in conformance with
293 Section 36-26-10, Code of Alabama 1975, may employ personnel
294 to operate the office including one employee who is in exempt
295 service and not subject to the state Merit System. This
296 position is in addition to any other exempt position otherwise
297 authorized by law for the department. The compensation of this
298 employee shall be set by the commissioner.
299 Section 9. This act shall become effective on October
300 1, 2026.
